ce:section.ce:para:
CDs preparation methods can be divided into top-down and bottom-up approaches [11] (see Fig. 1
                     ). The top-down approach cuts large-size of graphenes or carbon nanotubes into small-size quantum dots by using arc discharge [12,13], laser irradiation [13], or electrochemical oxidation [14] (see Table 1
                     ). The CDs obtained from the arc discharge method always show excellent fluorescence performance, the laser irradiation method could easily adjust CDs size, and the electrochemical oxidation method has good repeatability. However, such methods usually require complex instruments and consume expensive raw materials [2,10]. On the other hand, the bottom-up approach uses small organic molecules as precursors and produces CDs through a sequence of chemical reactions. This approach, with its benefits of a wide supply of precursors and simplicity of mechanization, appears to promise industrialization scale CDs production [15]. The bottom-up approach mainly includes template [16], combustion [17], acid oxidation [18], microwave [19], and hydrothermal methods [20] (see Table 1). The template method can prevent the agglomeration of CDs particles and control CDs size effectively [9], but its operation is relatively complicated. The combustion method is simple in operation and low in cost [21], but the obtained CDs may display low photoluminescence quantum yield (PLQY). CDs prepared by the acid oxidation method have a small size and excellent fluorescence performance, but the process would produce acid refractory waste and cause increased toxicity of CDs [22]. The microwave technology offers advantages of simple operation, fast speed, and high PLQY [15], but it would consume large amounts of electricity. In terms of the hydrothermal method, it has merits of simple operation, strong controllability, environmental friendliness [23,24], and is capable to run by using waste heat. Therefore, the hydrothermal method has attracted widespread attention for the production of CDs in recent years [2].
